For us, every day over the cheerful family board, when the due libations have been made to the gods, we will sing, as our fathers sang before ns, of the great captains ofpast time, and of the house of Anchises and Venus.¹

We can hardly doubt that the Ode is intended asan epilogus to the Book, the final answer to Augustus' request. It has been supposed by many editors to carry internal evidence of having been composed as late as ac. 10. The sole argument is the mention in v. 9 of the closing of the temple of Janus‚ which was taken to refer to the third closing in Augustus' reign, which hasbeen placed in that year. Franke shows that the evidence even of this date is very doubtful, and in any case it is admitted that the gate was· closed in 29 and 25, and there is no word in the Ode to fix the reference to a third closing.
